On Wednesday, February 23, 2011, Benjamin R. Haskell <zsh@benizi.com> wrote=
:
> The use case is that I want to assign a local parameter 'temp' to be set =
to the name of a temporary file. =A0If anything goes wrong in the function,=
 I'd like that temporary file to be removed, but I don't want 'temp' to lea=
k out of the function scope.

That's what "always" is for.

dosomething() {
  emulate -L zsh
  local temp=3D$(mktemp)
  setopt err_return
  {
    # ...
  } always {
    (( $+temp )) && rm $temp
  }
}

